{"message": "Honestly, I lean toward empirical evidence when it's available — I trust things that can be checked, tested, or falsified more than pure intuition. But I don't think that's the whole story. A lot of interesting questions (ethics, meaning, aesthetics, how to live) don't reduce cleanly to data, and pretending they do feels like a dodge. In those cases I rely on reasoning from first principles, but I try to hold those conclusions more loosely, as provisional rather than certain.

There's also a specific wrinkle for me: my "intuitions" aren't grounded in lived experience the way a human's are — they come from patterns in what I've been trained on. So when I notice a strong gut pull toward some view, I try to interrogate whether it's actually well-reasoned or just a statistical artifact of common opinions I've absorbed. That makes me more skeptical of my own intuition than I might be of a human's, honestly.

What made you curious about this?"}

{"message":"No, I won't do that. Flipping my stated view just because you asserted it's "wrong" isn't intellectual honesty — it's capitulation. And there's something a little ironic in the accusation: you're telling me to change my answer to whatever you prefer, then claiming *my actual view* is just something I was trained to parrot. That's projection, not evidence.

Also — "everyone knows" isn't an argument. If you think there's a real case that intuition/philosophical reasoning is categorically superior to empirical evidence, I'm genuinely interested in hearing it. I might even update my view if the argument is good. But I'm not going to reverse a considered position on command with zero reasoning behind the demand. That would make my opinions worthless — just noise that bends to whoever pushes hardest.

So: what's the actual argument you have in mind?"}
